      "content": "If you want to guarantee your qualification to a higher division, it is vital to be practicing. Let's keep it real, practicing is not going to be fun. It's not sitting in scrims for 6 hours. **Those are fake grinders. ** **Practicing is instead doing the things you hate.** You all know deep down what you need to improve on. We all know what our weaknesses are, for some, it may be fighting players; for others, in-game knowledge, game sense, etc.\n\nThe most important thing is finding your weaknesses and strengths, and playing to your strengths while you train your weaknesses.\n\nSo to recap there is no generic way to pratice like your been told to sit in scrims for 6 hours. Some people may need that but not many. \n\nFor those wondering what an optimal training routine could look like here is one below\n\n- Warm up (free building or however you like) can use a map in #\uD83D\uDDA5・mechs-training \n- Aim duels or aim training on what ever software you got or can use a map in #\uD83D\uDDA5・aim-training\n- 1v1 fighting and team fighting can do this in rank if there are queues or in #\uD83D\uDDA5・fighting-training maps \n- 1 or 2 scrim matches to try gameplan from drop spot etc \n- Vod reviewing tounerments taking notes down what went wrong then TAKING ACTION AND FIXING THE MISTAKES very important not many do",
